<li id="cite_note-Assault_Weapon_media_invention-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Assault_Weapon_media_invention_10-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Assault_Weapon_media_invention_10-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation news">Kauffman, Matthew (December 18, 2012). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://articles.courant.com/2012-12-18/news/hc-newtown-assault-weapons-20121217_1_assault-weapon-lethal-weapon-rifle">"In State With 'Assault Weapons' Ban, Lanza's Rifle Still Legal"</a>. <i>The Courant</i> (Hartford, Connecticut)<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved January 2, 2013</span>. "The term 'assault weapon,' as used by the media, is a media invention. These are semi-automatic firearms that have military cosmetic characteristics. They look like our military firearms, but they're not."</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAssault+weapon&amp;rft.atitle=In+State+With+%27Assault+Weapons%27+Ban%2C+Lanza%27s+Rifle+Still+Legal&amp;rft.au=Kauffman%2C+Matthew&amp;rft.aulast=Kauffman%2C+Matthew&amp;rft.date=December+18%2C+2012&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farticles.courant.com%2F2012-12-18%2Fnews%2Fhc-newtown-assault-weapons-20121217_1_assault-weapon-lethal-weapon-rifle&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Courant&amp;rft.place=Hartford%2C+Connecticut&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-intentional_confusion-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-intentional_confusion_11-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-intentional_confusion_11-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web">Tartaro, Joseph P. (1995). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.saf.org/LawReviews/Tartaro1.htm">"The Great Assault Weapon Hoax"</a>. University of Dayton Law Review Symposium, Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994, vol. 20, no. 2, 1995: 557<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved January 3, 2013</span>. "One of the key elements of the anti-gun strategy to gull the public into supporting bans on the so-called "assault weapons" is to foster confusion. As stated previously, the public does not know the difference between a full automatic and a semi-automatic firearm. They have been further hoodwinked by the television charades of people like New York's former Governor Mario Cuomo talking about semi-automatic firearms while the camera shows a full automatic firing. Fully automatic weapons have been strictly regulated and registered since 1934. Real assault weapons are controlled by the 1934 law and by laws in most states. There is no need for a new law on semi-automatic firearms. However, the anti-gunners responsible for the hoax have continued to perpetuate it by exploiting public confusion."</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAssault+weapon&amp;rft.aulast=Tartaro%2C+Joseph+P.&amp;rft.au=Tartaro%2C+Joseph+P.&amp;rft.btitle=The+Great+Assault+Weapon+Hoax&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.saf.org%2FLawReviews%2FTartaro1.htm&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Dayton+Law+Review+Symposium%2C+Violent+Crime+Control+and+Law+Enforcement+Act+of+1994%2C+vol.+20%2C+no.+2%2C+1995%3A+557&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#