<li id="cite_note-Sugarmann_popularized-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Sugarmann_popularized_12-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Sugarmann_popularized_12-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation news">Blake, Aaron (January 17, 2013). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/01/17/is-it-fair-to-call-them-assault-weapons/">"Is it fair to call them ‘assault weapons’?"</a>. <i>Washington Post</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved January 30, 2013</span>. "The term 'assault weapon' became widely used starting the late 1980s. Many attribute its popularization to a 1988 paper written by gun-control activist and Violence Policy Center founder Josh Sugarmann and the later reaction to a mass shooting at a Stockton, Calif., school in January 1989."</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAssault+weapon&amp;rft.atitle=Is+it+fair+to+call+them+%E2%80%98assault+weapons%E2%80%99%3F&amp;rft.au=Blake%2C+Aaron&amp;rft.aulast=Blake%2C+Aaron&amp;rft.date=January+17%2C+2013&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fblogs%2Fthe-fix%2Fwp%2F2013%2F01%2F17%2Fis-it-fair-to-call-them-assault-weapons%2F&amp;rft.jtitle=Washington+Post&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
